Description: A benign fibrous histiocytoma is a noncancerous tumor derived from fibrous tissue of the dermis layer of the skin, typically appearing as a small, firm, solitary nodule.
This is a disease characterized by degenerative changes in joints caused by damage to or disease of the nervous system.

Epithelioid hemangioendothelioma is a rare vascular cancer that predominantly impacts the soft tissues, liver and lungs, showing characteristics akin to both benign hemangiomas and highly malignant angiosarcomas.
Alzheimer's disease is a progressive neurological disorder that results in memory loss, intellectual impairment, and changes in behavior and personality, often leading to severe dementia.

Disease Term: Classical Lissencephalies and Subcortical Band Heterotopias
Description: These are genetic disorders characterized by abnormalities in the cerebral cortex's development, leading to impaired cognitive functions and muscle control.
Liposarcoma is a rare type of cancer that originates in the fat cells and tends to occur in the deep soft tissues of the limbs or in the abdomen.
This is a heart condition where the two valve flaps of the mitral valve don't close smoothly or evenly, causing them to balloon (prolapse) into the left atrium each time the heart contracts.
Gallbladder Neoplasms are abnormal, potentially cancerous growths that develop in the gallbladder, a small organ below the liver that stores bile.
A Port-Wine Stain is a type of birthmark that appears as a red or purple discoloration on the skin, typically on the face, due to abnormal development of blood vessels.
These are abnormal growths that develop in the pituitary gland, which can disrupt hormonal balance and function, and are usually benign but can be malignant.
Proliferative vitreoretinopathy is an eye disorder characterized by the growth of scar tissue on the retina, leading to vision loss and potentially retinal detachment.
Duodenal diseases are conditions that affect the duodenum, the first part of the small intestine, and can include ulcers, tumors, and infections among other issues.

Refractive errors are vision problems that occur when the shape of the eye doesn't refract light properly, causing blurred images on the retina which lead to conditions like myopia (nearsightedness), hyperopia (farsightedness), astigmatism (distorted vision), and presbyopia (aging eye condition).
Myoclonus refers to a condition characterized by sudden, involuntary jerking of a muscle or group of muscles.
Bipolar Disorder is a mental health condition characterized by severe mood swings that include emotional highs (mania or hypomania) and lows (depression).
This is a group of inherited disorders that cause nerve damage, primarily in the arms and legs, leading to muscle weakness and loss of sensation.
This is a condition characterized by bleeding in any segment of the gastrointestinal tract from mouth to anus.
Adult Respiratory Distress Syndrome is a severe lung condition often caused by acute injury to the lungs, characterized by rapid breathing, shortness of breath, and insufficient oxygen in the blood.
These are conditions that affect the coordination and control of eye movements, potentially causing problems like double vision or strabismus (misaligned eyes).
Facial Asymmetry is a condition characterised by uneven or unbalanced proportions of the face due to differences in size and shape of facial features on opposite sides.
Gerstmann-Straussler-Scheinker Disease is a rare, inherited neurodegenerative disorder characterized by progressive ataxia, spasticity, and dementia.
Coloboma is a congenital eye condition characterized by the incomplete development of certain eye structures, leading to missing pieces or gaps in the eye.
Muscle Hypotonia is a condition characterized by decreased muscle tone, often resulting in reduced muscle strength, and difficulty in movement or posture maintenance.
Esophageal Neoplasms are tumors or growths in the esophagus that can be benign (noncancerous) or malignant (cancerous).

Adrenocortical Hyperfunction is a condition where the adrenal glands produce excess amounts of cortisol, leading to symptoms such as weight gain, high blood pressure, and osteoporosis.

Obstructive lung diseases are a category of respiratory conditions characterized by difficulty exhaling all the air in the lungs due to damage to the lungs or narrowing of the airways.
These are illnesses caused by an acute infection which involves different parts of the body's airway tract like the sinuses, throat, pharynx, larynx, bronchi, or lungs.
These are a group of conditions where the reproductive organs and genitals do not develop as expected, leading to variations in the usual patterns of sexual development.

Myocardial Stunning refers to a temporary state of diminished function of the heart muscle following stress, such as from lack of blood supply or oxygen.

This condition is characterized by involuntary, erratic body movements side-effect resulting from long-term usage of certain medications, specifically drugs used to treat psychiatric disorders and Parkinson's disease.
A chronic eye disorder that results in vision loss in the center field of vision caused by damage to the retina.
Marfan Syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the body's connective tissue, leading to problems with the heart, blood vessels, bones, joints, and eyes.
Muscular diseases encompass a variety of disorders that cause progressive weakness and loss of muscle mass due to dysfunctional proteins or affected cells relating to muscle health.
It is a disorder characterized by low levels of serum immunoglobulins (antibodies) in the blood, leading to increased vulnerability to infections.
Hepatomegaly is a condition characterized by an enlarged liver, often indicative of underlying disorders such as hepatitis, congestive heart failure, or cirrhosis.
This is a condition characterized by the inability to control bowel movements, leading to an involuntary passage of stool.
This is a progressive kidney disease caused by damage to the small blood vessels in the kidneys related to long-term diabetes.
A rare, inherited disorder characterized by distinctive facial features, small head size, intellectual disability, and multiple malformations.
It is an inflammation of the nerves in the brachial plexus, causing sudden, severe pain in the shoulder and arm, often leading to weakness and numbness.

Hyperemia is a medical condition characterized by an excessive amount of blood in body parts or organs, typically caused by increased blood flow due to inflammation, infection, or the presence of a blockage.

Aortic Valve Stenosis is a cardiac condition characterized by the narrowing of the aortic valve in the heart, which restricts blood flow and forces the heart to work harder to pump blood throughout the body.
Cardiovascular abnormalities refer to any disorders or defects in the heart or blood vessels which can lead to conditions like heart disease or stroke.

A rare, life-threatening neurological disorder characterized by a gradual and progressive decline in cognitive ability, behavior and motor skills due to persistent measles virus infection in the brain.
Niemann-Pick Disease, Type C is a rare genetic disorder affecting lipid metabolism and resulting in harmful amounts of lipids accumulating in the spleen, liver, lungs, bone marrow, and brain.

Porphyrias are a group of rare genetic disorders that affect the nervous system and skin, resulting from a buildup of certain chemicals related to red blood cell proteins.

Skin diseases encompass a wide variety of conditions that affect the skin, ranging from benign dermatoses to life-threatening skin cancers, encompassing conditions like eczema, psoriasis, and dermatitis.
Blepharophimosis is a congenital condition characterized by severe eyelid abnormalities, such as narrow eye openings, that can cause limited vision or difficulty closing the eyes.
These are a group of syndromes caused by the exposure to substances that are toxic to the nervous system, leading to symptoms like cognitive, motor, and sensory impairments.
This is a form of epilepsy characterized by myoclonic and generalized tonic-clonic seizures often starting in adolescence.

Pulmonary Hypertension refers to a type of high blood pressure that affects the arteries in the lungs and the right side of the heart.
Progressive Myoclonic Epilepsies are a group of neurological disorders characterized by myoclonic seizures, progressive neurological dysfunction, and other types of seizures.

It's a lung infection characterized by inflammation of the air sacs, which may fill with fluid or pus, causing cough with phlegm, fever, chills, and shortness of breath.
It's a genetic disorder leading to defects in the body's ability to metabolize fats or lipids, causing an accumulation of specific lipid types that can lead to health problems.

Syncope is a temporary loss of consciousness usually related to insufficient blood flow to the brain.

Glioblastoma is a fast-growing, aggressive type of central nervous system tumor that forms on the supportive tissue of the brain.

These are disorders that result from damage to a region of the brain responsible for controlling movements, which can lead to symptoms such as involuntary or uncontrolled movements, loss of motor coordination, and problems with physical speaking and swallowing.
This is a condition caused by reduced oxygen or blood flow to the brain, often leading to neuronal damage and potential cognitive or physical impairments.

This condition occurs when the body's balance of key minerals, like sodium and potassium, required for normal body function is disrupted, causing a variety of symptoms depending on the mineral involved.
Laryngeal diseases are disorders affecting the larynx (voice box), that may lead to voice changes, difficulty swallowing, or breathing problems.
Hodgkin Disease is a type of lymphoma, which is a blood cancer that originates in the lymphatic system, causing the cells in the lymph nodes to change and grow out of control.

Supravalvular Aortic Stenosis is a heart condition characterized by a narrowing of the section of the aorta just above the aortic valve, resulting in restricted blood flow, increased heart workload and potentially heart damage.

Wolfram Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus, optic atrophy leading to blindness, diabetes insipidus and deafness.

Ulcerative Colitis is a chronic inflammatory bowel disease characterized by inflammation and ulcers in the innermost lining of the colon and rectum.

Joint instability is a condition characterized by the excessive, often abnormal, movement of specific joints due to weakened or stretched ligaments and muscles.
This is a condition characterized by insufficient production and secretion of pancreatic enzymes, leading to difficulty digesting food and absorbing nutrients.

Essential Thrombocythemia is a rare chronic blood disorder characterized by the overproduction of platelets by the bone marrow, potentially leading to blood clotting and bleeding events.
Microcephaly is a birth defect where a baby's head is significantly smaller than expected due to abnormal brain development in the womb or halted growth after birth.
Brain injuries are damages to the brain that impair its functions and can result from trauma, lack of oxygen, infections, or medical conditions.
This is a type of cancer where the body produces an excessive amount of immature white blood cells, preventing the normal formation and function of other blood cells.
Rolandic epilepsy is a common type of childhood epilepsy that causes seizures affecting the face and throat, as well as unusual brain activity during sleep.

This is a process where cells acquire the properties of neoplasms (abnormal tissue growths), including uncontrolled growth, ability to metastasize (spread), and survival past the normal cellular life cycle.
Chronic Kidney Failure refers to the gradual loss of kidney function, resulting in the build-up of waste, water, and other toxins in the body that the kidneys can't remove.

This is a rare genetic disorder characterized by poor muscle tone, impaired growth, developmental delay, and the inability of cells to use oxygen, which can cause damage to many of the body's systems, particularly the nervous system and the heart.
Ichthyosis is a group of skin disorders characterized by dry, thickened, and scaly skin affecting either all or certain parts of the body.
These are conditions that lead to deterioration or abnormalities in the structure or function of the skeleton, affecting bone density, shape, and strength.
Urogenital Abnormalities refer to birth defects or disorders related to the urinary and reproductive systems, potentially impacting kidneys, bladder, genitalia or the reproductive process.
A genetic disorder characterized by thickening of the heart muscle, making it harder for the heart to pump blood.

These are a variety of disorders that involve dysfunctions in the body's connective tissues, which include elements like collagen and elastin, and may manifest in conditions like lupus, rheumatoid arthritis, and Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome.

An aneurysm is a bulge or ballooning in the wall of an artery, often appearing in the aorta or the brain, which can lead to life-threatening complications if it ruptures.
Behcet Syndrome is a chronic and rare disorder that causes inflammation in blood vessels throughout the body, often characterized by recurrent oral and genital sores and eye inflammation.
This condition refers to a woman's inability to conceive and become pregnant despite having regular unprotected sex for at least a year.
Glioma is a type of tumor that starts in the glial cells of the brain or the spine.

Dyssomnias are a group of sleep disorders characterized by difficulty falling asleep, staying asleep, or experiencing excessive sleepiness.

Hydrocephalus is a condition characterized by an excessive accumulation of fluid in the brain, potentially causing developmental, physical, and intellectual impairments.
These are conditions or abnormalities that affect the sweat glands leading to excessive sweating, insufficient sweating, or infections within the sweat ducts.

Duane Retraction Syndrome is a rare, congenital eye movement disorder characterized by restricted horizontal eye movement, retraction of the eyeball into the socket and, in some cases, other eye abnormalities.

Methemoglobinemia is a blood disorder characterized by an increased level of methemoglobin, a form of hemoglobin that has a reduced ability to release oxygen to body tissues.

Dwarfism is a medical condition that leads to short stature, usually resulting from a genetic mutation affecting bone growth.

Hemorrhage refers to excessive or uncontrolled bleeding from blood vessels often due to trauma, surgery, or certain medical conditions.

Learning disorders are neurologically-based disorders that cause difficulties with acquiring basic academic skills such as reading, writing, and math.
Penile diseases refer to any abnormal conditions that affect the penis, including skin conditions, cancers, Peyronie's disease, erectile dysfunction, and sexually transmitted diseases.

Long QT Syndrome is a heart rhythm condition that can cause fast, chaotic heartbeats, potentially leading to fainting, seizures, or sudden death.

Anodontia is a genetic condition characterized by the complete absence of teeth, either primary or permanent.

Stomach Neoplasms are abnormal growths in the stomach which can be benign or malignant, with gastric cancer being a common type.

A congenital deformity caused by a non-fusion of the body's natural structures that form the palate, causing a gap in the roof of the mouth that can impact speech, hearing, and feeding.

It is a severe injury to the skull or brain mechanisms often caused by physical trauma, impacting the brain functionality and health to a significant extent.

Rheumatoid Arthritis is a chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet, characterized by painful swelling, resulting in joint deformity and erosion.

This is a genetic condition characterized by the development of certain types of cancer, particularly cancers of the colon and rectum, at an early age.
Hereditary Nephritis, also known as Alport Syndrome, is a genetic disorder characterized by kidney disease, hearing loss, and eye abnormalities.
Infections are caused by invading pathogens such as bacteria, viruses, or fungi, leading to illness and immune response in the body.

Metabolic bone diseases are disorders of bone strength usually caused by abnormalities of minerals, vitamin D, bone mass or bone structure, and often resulting in fractures and pain.

These are conditions that involve inflammation, injury, or other pathologies affecting the anus, which could include hemorrhoids, abscesses, fistulas, and cancers, causing symptoms like pain, itching, bleeding, or difficulty in passing stools.
These are bacterial infections transmitted to humans through consumption of contaminated animal-origin products and may cause symptoms such as diarrhea, fever and abdominal cramps.
A condition where an individual is unable to conceive or cause conception naturally after one year (or six months if they're over 35) of unprotected sex.

Uveitis is an inflammation of the uvea, the middle layer of the eye, which can lead to reduced vision or blindness if left untreated.

This refers to an individual's increased likelihood of developing particular diseases due to variations in their genes.
Cryopyrin-Associated Periodic Syndromes are a group of rare hereditary inflammatory disorders characterized by episodes of fever, rash and joint pain, often provoked by cold exposure.
Aphasia is a communication disorder that results from damage to the parts of the brain that contain language, affecting the production or comprehension of speech and the ability to read or write.
Tietze's Syndrome is a rare, inflammatory disorder characterized by chest pain and swelling of the cartilage of one or more of the upper ribs.

Mood disorders are psychological conditions characterized by the consistent, long-term alteration of a person's mood, leading to severe disturbances in daily life and often categorized as depressive, bipolar, and mood disorders related to other health conditions.
Frasier Syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by kidney disease, abnormal gonad development, and a higher risk of specific types of cancer, primarily occurring in females.

Myotonic Disorders refer to a spectrum of inherited, neuromuscular conditions characterized by muscle stiffness (myotonia) and progressive muscle weakness.
Hyperinsulinism is a condition characterized by excess levels of insulin in the bloodstream, often resulting in low blood sugar (hypoglycemia).
Hyperopia is a common vision condition in which distant objects can be seen clearly, but close ones do not come into proper focus.
Micrognathism is a condition characterized by an unusually small or underdeveloped lower jaw, often leading to difficulties with feeding or breathing.

Hoarseness is a condition characterized by abnormal voice changes, which may range from a raspy tone to weak voice, often as a result of irritation or injury to the vocal cords.
These are conditions marked by inflammation, pain, and stiffness in the muscles or joints, including ailments like arthritis and lupus.

Nerve Degeneration refers to the progressive deterioration and loss of function in neurons, which are essential cells of the nervous system.
Muscular Dystrophies are a group of genetic diseases that result in progressive weakness and loss of muscle mass.
Progeria is a rare genetic disorder characterized by accelerated aging in children, resulting in a significantly shorter life span due to conditions normally associated with advanced age.
These are disorders characterized by difficulties with verbal and verbal-visual memory, complex language expression, comprehension, and certain motor skills affecting speech.

These are a set of disorders marked by abnormal blood clotting processes leading to either a higher tendency for excessive bleeding or abnormal clotting.

Homocystinuria is a genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of the amino acid methionine, leading to a buildup of homocysteine in the body, potentially causing complications such as vision problems, skeletal abnormalities, blood clotting issues, and cognitive impairment.
These are abnormal growths or tumors in the brain that can be benign (non-cancerous) or malignant (cancerous), whose symptoms and effects largely depend on their size and location within the brain.
Sepsis is a life-threatening condition triggered by the body's extreme response to an infection, which can lead to tissue damage, organ failure, and even death.

Rickets is a skeletal disorder in children caused predominantly by a vitamin D deficiency, which impairs the body's ability to absorb calcium and phosphorus, leading to softening and weakening of the bones.

Opioid-Related Disorders are a group of conditions characterized by addiction, dependency or misuse of opioids such as prescription pain medication or illegal drugs like heroin.

Experimental Arthritis is a type of inflammation of the joints that is induced for research purposes to study the disease process, potential therapeutics and to better understand the pathophysiology of different forms of arthritis.
Movement disorders are neurological conditions that affect the speed, fluency, quality, and ease of motor functions, often producing abnormal voluntary and involuntary movements.
Hypoparathyroidism is a rare condition in which the body produces insufficient amounts of parathyroid hormone, resulting in low levels of calcium in the blood and an overabundance of phosphorus.

Anophthalmos is a severe disorder characterized by the absence of one or both eyes at birth.
These are a group of disorders caused by poorly formed blood cells or ones that don't work properly, resulting in an inability to produce enough healthy blood cells.

Renal Cell Carcinoma is a type of kidney cancer that starts in the lining of the tiny tubes (tubules) in the kidney.
Hemochromatosis is a disorder causing your body to absorb too much iron from the food you eat, leading to iron overload, which can result in damage to organs like the liver and heart.
An abnormal reflex is a response to certain stimuli that is either unusually weak, absent, or exaggerated, indicating potential problems in the central or peripheral nervous system.

Leukoencephalopathies are a group of rare, progressive, metabolic, genetic diseases that affect the brain, spinal cord and often the peripheral nerves, characterized by degeneration of the white matter in the central nervous system.
Pelger-Huet Anomaly is a rare, inherited condition characterized by the abnormal development of certain white blood cells, which doesn't usually cause any symptoms or health problems.
Leiomyoma is a noncancerous growth often occurring in the uterus and composed of smooth muscle and fibrous connective tissue.

Description: These are genetic disorders characterized by the progressive loss of the myelin sheath, a protective covering of nerve cells, within the central nervous system, leading to a range of neurological symptoms.
These are hereditary conditions characterized by progressive degeneration and loss of function in the nerves within the nervous system.
Ataxia Telangiectasia is a rare, inherited neurodegenerative disease characterized by severe impairment of muscle control, immune system problems, and a high rate of cancer.
Ectodermal Dysplasia is a genetic disorder affecting the development and function of the teeth, hair, nails and sweat glands.

Muscular Atrophy is a medical condition characterized by a decrease in muscle mass, often due to lack of physical activity, age, malnutrition, or underlying disease, leading to weakness or limited mobility.

Acute Coronary Syndrome is a medical condition characterized by sudden, reduced blood flow to the heart leading to symptoms such as chest pain, shortness of breath, or sweating.
Splenomegaly is a condition characterized by an enlargement of the spleen, often due to infections, liver diseases, or blood cancers.

Urinary Calculi refers to the condition where hard, stone-like material forms in the urinary tract or kidneys, often as a result of concentrated urine.

Blepharoptosis is a condition characterized by drooping or falling of the upper or lower eyelid.

Tourette Syndrome is a neurological disorder characterized by repetitive, stereotyped, involuntary movements and vocalizations called tics.

Dysostoses are a group of disorders characterized by abnormal growth and development of bones and joints.
Burns are injuries to tissues caused by heat, friction, electricity, radiation, or chemicals.

Hypoglycemia is a condition characterized by an abnormally low level of blood sugar (glucose), the body's main energy source.

A rare, genetic disorder characterized by the progressive loss of myelin, a fatty covering that insulates nerve fibers and leads to neurological and physical disability or death.

Mitochondrial Myopathies are a group of neuromuscular diseases caused by damage to the mitochondria, leading to muscle weakness, neurological issues, and organ dysfunction.

Aniridia is a rare genetic disorder characterized by a partial or complete absence of the iris (the colored part of the eye), often accompanied with other visual impairments including sensitivity to light and poor vision.

A sudden, brief period of symptoms similar to those of stroke, typically caused due to a temporary decrease in blood supply to part of the brain.

Nonketotic Hyperglycinemia is a metabolic disorder characterized by significantly high levels of glycine in the body, leading to severe physical and intellectual disability.
Prostatitis is an inflammation or infection of the prostate gland that presents symptoms such as frequent urination or discomfort, pain in the pelvic area, and sometimes flu-like symptoms.
Multiple organ failure refers to the progressive dysfunction or failure of two or more organ systems in a critically ill patient due to a catastrophic event like severe injury or infection.
Hypokalemia is a condition characterized by low levels of potassium in the blood which is essential for proper functioning of cells, tissues, and organs.
Retinal diseases are a variety of disorders that affect the retina, a layer of nerve tissue in the back of the eye that senses light and sends images to the brain.

Acidosis, Lactic is a serious medical condition characterized by the build-up of lactic acid in the blood, which can result from prolonged exercise, severe dehydration, or certain medical conditions such as sepsis and cancer.

These are viral infections caused by the Arenaviridae family, known to cause severe diseases such as Lassa fever and meningitis, predominantly spread through contact with infected rodents or their droppings.

Sarcoidosis is an inflammatory disease characterized by the abnormal formation of tiny granulomas or clumps of inflammatory cells in different parts of the body, frequently affecting the lungs, lymph nodes, eyes, and skin.

Parathyroid neoplasms are abnormal growths on the parathyroid glands, which regulate calcium levels in the body, and can lead to hyperparathyroidism, characterized by excessively high levels of parathyroid hormone.
Hyperplasia is a condition characterized by the excessive growth of cells within an organ or tissue in a body, increasing its size.
These are abnormal growths or tumors, often cancerous, that develop in the organs or tissues of the head or neck, such as the nasal cavity, oral cavity, throat, thyroid, larynx, or paranasal sinuses.

Isaacs Syndrome is a rare, autoimmune neuromuscular disorder characterized by continuous muscle activity, such as twitching and stiffness, with symptoms often including cramping, weakness, and reduced muscle relaxation.

This is a birth defect where an infant's hip joint is not properly formed, allowing for easy displacement or full dislocation.
Substance Withdrawal Syndrome is a group of symptoms that occur upon the abrupt discontinuation or decrease in intake of medications or recreational drugs.

Postpartum depression is a mood disorder that can affect women after childbirth, causing feelings of extreme sadness, anxiety, and exhaustion that may interfere with their ability to care for themselves or their family.

Hypoalbuminemia is a disorder characterized by an abnormally low level of albumin, a major protein, in the blood often associated with malnutrition, liver disease, kidney disease, and inflammation.

It's a genetic condition where a person who is genetically male (who has one X and one Y chromosome) is resistant to male hormones (androgens), causing them to have physical traits of a female but genetic makeup of a male.
Testicular Neoplasms are abnormal growths or tumors that develop in the testes, often identified by an unusual lump or swelling and can be benign or malignant.

An autoimmune disorder which results in the premature destruction of red blood cells by the body's own immune system, leading to an insufficient amount of red blood cells to carry oxygen to bodily tissues.
Pyoderma Gangrenosum is a rare skin condition marked by large, painful sores typically on the legs but can develop anywhere on the body.

Pulmonary valve stenosis involves a narrowing of the pulmonary valve, affecting the flow of blood from the heart to the lungs.
Li-Fraumeni Syndrome is a rare, inherited disorder that greatly increases the risk of developing several types of cancer, particularly in young adults and children.
Familial Mediterranean Fever is a genetic disorder characterized by recurrent episodes of painful inflammation in the abdomen, chest, or joints.

Ventricular fibrillation is a life-threatening heart rhythm disorder characterized by rapid and irregular electrical impulses causing the ventricles to quiver ineffectively, leading to a decrease or halt in blood pumping.
Pernicious anemia is a condition that involves a decrease in red blood cells caused by the body's inability to absorb vitamin B12.
Seizures are a sudden, uncontrolled electrical disturbance in the brain which can cause changes in behavior, movements, feelings, and levels of consciousness.
Sjogren's Syndrome is an autoimmune disorder characterized by dry mouth and dry eyes, as the body's immune system mistakenly attacks its own moisture-producing glands.
An inflammatory condition of the inner lining of the colon, often caused by infections, poor blood supply, or autoimmune reactions.
Rectal Neoplasms are growths or tumors in the rectum that can be benign (noncancerous) or malignant (cancerous).

Cutaneous Leishmaniasis is a parasitic infection spread by the bite of sandflies which results in skin ulcers, typically on exposed parts of the body, and can cause scars after healing.
Pulmonary fibrosis is a lung disease that occurs when lung tissue becomes damaged and scarred, making it difficult for your lungs to work properly.
An autoimmune disease where the body's immune system mistakenly attacks its own tissues and organs, resulting in inflammation and damage to various body systems.

Eyelid diseases encompass a range of conditions that affect the skin, muscles, or other tissues of the eyelids and can cause symptoms including redness, swelling, itching, pain, tearing, or visual disturbances.
Polycystic Kidney Diseases are genetic disorders that cause numerous cysts to grow in the kidneys, which can impair kidney function and eventually lead to kidney failure.
Poisoning is a condition that occurs when an organism ingests, inhales, injects, or absorbs a substance that causes physical harm or disrupts normal body functions.
Ophthalmoplegia is a condition characterized by the paralysis or weakness in some or all of the muscles that control eye movement, leading to limited or even lost control of one or both eyes.

Multiple Myeloma is a type of blood cancer that develops within the bone marrow, leading to an overproduction of cancerous plasma cells which can weaken the immune system, cause anemia, and lead to bone and kidney damage.
Chronic Granulomatous Disease is a rare, genetic disorder that impairs the immune system, making the body susceptible to bacterial and fungal infections.
Arteriovenous Malformations (AVMs) are defects in the vascular system characterized by abnormal, snarled tangles of blood vessels which cause irregular connections between the arteries and veins.
Lipidoses is a group of genetic disorders characterized by the accumulation of excess lipids, including fats and cholesterol, in cells and tissues of the body.
Glomerulonephritis is an inflammation of the small blood vessels in the kidneys that filter waste and excess water from the blood to create urine.
Neurofibromatosis 1 is a genetic disorder that causes the growth of tumors on the nerves in the skin, brain, and other parts of the body.

Inborn errors of Purine-Pyrimidine Metabolism refer to a group of rare genetic disorders characterized by defects in the body's ability to produce or break down purines and pyrimidines, the building blocks of DNA and RNA.

Neurofibromatosis 2 is a genetic disorder characterized by the growth of noncancerous tumors in the nervous system, specifically on the nerves that carry sound and balance information from the inner ear to the brain.

These are disorders caused by mutations in genes on the X chromosome, often leading to conditions such as color blindness, hemophilia, and certain types of muscular dystrophy, and can affect males more severely due to their having only one X chromosome.
It is a condition where there is an abnormal opening in the diaphragm, allowing part of the organs in the abdomen to move into the chest cavity.
Hyperkalemia is a condition characterized by an abnormally high concentration of potassium in the blood, which can lead to heart problems.

Eye Abnormalities refer to a wide range of conditions that negatively affect the normal function and structure of the eyes, which can be congenital or acquired and include issues like cataracts, glaucoma, or macular degeneration.
Pruritus is an unsettling skin condition characterized by severe itching, often with no visible signs on the skin.
Migraine Disorders are characterized by recurring, intense, and debilitating headaches often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound.
A benign tumor of blood vessels often appearing as a birthmark that fades away over time.
Apraxias are neurological disorders characterized by the inability to perform learned (familiar) movements on command, despite having the desire and the physical ability to perform the movements.
Astrocytoma is a type of brain tumor that originates from star-shaped cells called astrocytes, which support nerve cells within the brain and spinal cord.

Rett Syndrome is a neurodevelopmental disorder, predominantly affecting females, characterized by severe cognitive impairments, loss of purposeful hand skills, and distinctive hand movements like hand-wringing.
An autoimmune disorder characterized by a severe decrease in the number of platelets in the blood, resulting in spontaneous bleeding or bruising.
Dysgammaglobulinemia is a group of disorders characterized by abnormal quantities or properties of the immune system's gamma globulins, leading to frequent infections or autoimmune diseases.
Urinary Incontinence is a common condition characterized by the inability to control urination, leading to unintentional leakage of urine.
Oral candidiasis is a fungal infection within the mouth, often characterized by white lesions, redness, and soreness, commonly caused by an overgrowth of Candida yeast.
Inflammatory Bowel Diseases are chronic conditions characterized by inflammation in the digestive tract, often categorized into two types: Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis.
Inclusion Body Myositis is a progressive muscle disorder characterized by muscle inflammation, weakness, and atrophy (wasting), particularly affecting the limbs.

Secondary Parkinson disease is a neurological disorder characterized by a wide range of motor and non-motor symptoms caused by conditions or factors other than degeneration of dopamine-producing cells in the brain, such as drugs, toxins, or brain damage.

Acrocephalosyndactylia is a genetic disorder primarily characterized by skull deformities, distinctive facial features, and abnormalities in the hands and feet due to early fusion of certain bones in the skull and limbs.
A malignant neoplasm originating from transformed cells in the ducts of the pancreas leading to symptoms such as weight loss, jaundice, and abdominal pain.
These are disorders affecting the nerves that control involuntary body functions such as heart rate, blood pressure, digestion, and sweating.

Urologic diseases encompass a range of conditions affecting the urinary system including the kidneys, urinary bladder, urethra, and in males, reproductive organs, with conditions varying from urinary tract infections to prostate cancers.
Ventricular septal defects refer to a common congenital heart defect characterized by one or more holes in the wall that separates the right and left ventricles of the heart.
These are tumors originating from the thymus gland, often caused by abnormal cell growth, and may be benign (non-cancerous) or malignant (cancerous) in nature.

Vitamin E deficiency is a rare condition resulting from a diet lacking in vitamin E or the inability of the body to absorb the vitamin, which can lead to nerve and muscle damage, weakened immune function, and anemia.
Arteritis is an inflammation of the walls of the arteries, which can lead to arterial damage, decreased blood flow, and potential organ harm.

An aortic rupture is a critical condition characterized by the breakdown of the wall of the aorta, the largest blood vessel in the body, which can lead to severe internal bleeding and potentially death if not immediately treated.

A rare genetic disorder marked by skeletal abnormalities, such as short stature, and punctate calcifications present in cartilage throughout the body.

Nose diseases encompass a range of conditions such as deviated septum, rhinitis, sinusitis, nasal polyps, and nosebleeds, typically characterized by symptoms such as nasal congestion, runny nose, nosebleeds, loss of smell, and breathing difficulties.
Brugada Syndrome is a genetic disorder that causes a disruption in the function of the heart's electrical system, potentially leading to irregular heartbeats, fainting, and sudden cardiac death.
Pierre Robin Syndrome is a congenital condition characterized by an unusually small lower jaw, a tongue that falls back in the throat, and difficulty breathing.
Bronchiolitis Obliterans is a rare and severe lung disease that's characterized by inflammation and blockage of the lung's smallest airways, the bronchioles.
Spinal diseases encompass a range of disorders affecting the backbone and can lead to pain, weakness, or numbness due to issues like infections, injuries, tumors, or congenital defects.
Uterine prolapse is a condition where weakened pelvic muscles allow the uterus to descend into or protrude out of the vagina.

Alexander Disease is a rare, often fatal, neurodegenerative disorder characterized by an overabundance of a protein called GFAP that results in the destruction of white matter in the brain and developmental impairment.
Schistosomiasis is a tropical disease caused by a parasite found in contaminated water, leading to damage to the liver, intestines, lungs, and bladder over time.
Chronic Progressive External Ophthalmoplegia is a genetic disorder characterized by slowly progressive weakening of the eye muscles resulting in difficulty moving the eyes and drooping eyelids.
Insulin resistance is a condition in which the body's cells become less responsive to the hormone insulin, leading to higher levels of sugar in the blood.
Schistosomiasis mansoni is a chronic parasitic disease caused by a trematode worm, primarily affecting the liver, spleen and intestines.
Ear diseases are conditions that affect the anatomical structures of the ear, leading to a range of symptoms from pain and hearing loss to dizziness and tinnitus.

Pheochromocytoma is a rare tumor of the adrenal glands that can cause high blood pressure, rapid heartbeat, sweating, tremors, severe headaches, and episodic symptoms, which can lead to severe or life-threatening damage to other body systems.
Alagille Syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the liver, heart, skeleton, eyes and kidneys, hindering normal bile production and causing liver damage.

Intestinal polyposis is a condition characterized by the development of multiple polyps, a form of abnormal growth, in the lining of the intestines which may lead to an increased risk of colorectal cancer.

Bardet-Biedl Syndrome is a genetic disorder that impacts various systems of the body characterised by obesity, vision loss, kidney abnormalities, and intellectual impairment along with additional symptoms.

Agranulocytosis is a serious condition characterized by a severe and dangerous drop in the number of white blood cells, specifically granulocytes, which play a key role in the immune system's fight against infection.
Thalassemia is a blood disorder involving less than normal amounts of an oxygen-carrying protein in the blood, leading to anemia.
This is a common condition in newborns that causes yellowing of the skin and the whites of the eyes due to high levels of bilirubin, a byproduct of the normal breakdown of red blood cells.
Amyloidosis is a rare disease characterized by the buildup of abnormal proteins called amyloids in the body's organs and tissues, interfering with their normal functioning.
Abruptio Placentae is a condition in pregnancy where the placenta prematurely detaches from the uterus, potentially causing severe bleeding and harm to the mother and baby.

Thromboembolism is a serious condition characterized by the formation of a clot (thrombus) that blocks blood flow within a vessel, potentially leading to life-threatening complications such as stroke or heart attack.

This is a group of hereditary disorders that involve abnormal growth of tissue within the endocrine system, causing benign or malignant tumors in various glands.
Hypertriglyceridemia is a condition characterized by elevated levels of triglycerides, a type of fat (lipid), in the blood, which could increase the risk of developing heart disease.

Heroin dependence is a chronic relapsing condition characterized by the compulsive use of heroin despite harmful consequences, and the manifestation of withdrawal symptoms upon the cessation of its use.

This is a benign tumor composed of small, closely packed blood vessels, typically appearing as a red mark or birthmark on the skin during infancy which may grow larger over time before naturally regressing.
Insulinoma is a rare tumorous condition of the pancreas that overproduces insulin leading to severe hypoglycemia.
Frontotemporal Lobar Degeneration is a group of brain disorders characterized by progressive loss of certain brain functions, including language skills, emotional response, and executive functions.
It is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder that affects nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, leading to loss of muscle control.
This is a condition that hinders a fetus from growing at a normal rate in the womb, often leading to a baby being born smaller than the usual size for the pregnancy duration.

Meningococcal meningitis is a bacterial infection causing severe inflammation of the meninges, which are the protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord.
A condition that results from consuming a diet in which nutrients are either insufficient or in excess such that it causes health problems.
These are abnormal growths or tumors, either benign or cancerous, that form on the vulva, the external female genitalia.
A chronic condition that causes joint inflammation, stiffness, and pain, often worsened by age.
Meningococcal Infections are severe bacterial infections commonly manifesting as inflammation of the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord, and often leading to blood infections.
This is a chronic, progressive lung disease characterized by scarring and hardening of the lungs' tissues leading to difficulty in breathing and reduced oxygen supply to the body.
Lipodystrophy is a disorder characterized by abnormal or degenerative conditions of the body's adipose tissue, leading to the selective loss of fat in some areas and accumulation in others.
Paroxysmal Hemoglobinuria is a rare acquired disorder that leads to destruction of red blood cells and consequently causes symptoms such as fatigue, yellowing eyes and skin, and blood clots.

Tuberculosis is a highly contagious bacterial infection that primarily affects the lungs but can also impact other organs, characterized by symptoms such as chronic cough, fever, night sweats, and weight loss.

Epidermolysis Bullosa Dystrophica is a rare genetic condition characterized by the formation of blisters or erosions from minor injuries to the skin, requiring elaborate wound care and often severely impacting the patient's quality of life.
Facies is not a disease but a medical term used to describe the distinctive facial expressions or appearances associated with certain health conditions or diseases.

Strabismus is a condition that impairs one's ability to align both eyes simultaneously due to imbalances in the actions of muscles that rotate the eyes, resulting in the eyes pointing in different directions.
Febrile seizures are convulsions in young children that can occur in conjunction with a high body temperature, often due to infections or during the early stages of a fever.
Scurvy is a disease resulting from a deficiency of vitamin C, which is required for the synthesis of collagen in humans, characterized by gum disease, skin issues, and anemia.
Crohn's Disease is a chronic inflammatory bowel disease that affects the lining of the digestive tract.
Autoimmune thyroiditis is a condition where the body's immune system attacks the thyroid gland, resulting in inflammation and potentially affecting its ability to produce hormones.
Angelman Syndrome is a genetic disorder causing delayed development, problems with speech and balance, seizures, and often a happy demeanor.

Opsoclonus-Myoclonus Syndrome is a rare neurological disorder characterized by rapid, involuntary, multi-directional eye movements, muscle contractions, difficulty speaking, disturbed sleep patterns, and unsteady, trembling gait.

Pulmonary Blastoma is a rare and aggressive malignant tumor of the lung that resembles fetal lung tissue.

Ankylosis is a condition marked by stiffness or immobilization of a joint due to disease, trauma, surgery, or abnormal bone fusion.
These are a group of disorders caused by genetic mutations affecting the mitochondria in cells, leading to problems with brain and muscle function.

Uremia is a severe condition that occurs when the kidneys no longer function properly leading to a buildup of urea and other waste products in the bloodstream, often resulting in symptoms like fatigue, loss of appetite, headaches, and swelling due to excess fluid retention.

Hereditary corneal dystrophies are a group of genetic disorders characterized by progressive buildup of abnormal material in the cornea, leading to visual impairment.
Craniofacial abnormalities are a diverse group of deformities in the growth of the head and facial bones.
Parapsoriasis is a group of rare skin disorders that cause rashes or patches on the skin, often mistaken for psoriasis or dermatitis, but can sometimes develop into a form of skin lymphoma.

Enuresis is a condition characterized by involuntary urination, especially by children during sleep, commonly referred to as bedwetting.

Cellulitis is a common, potentially serious bacterial skin infection marked by swelling and redness that often occurs in the lower legs but can occur anywhere on the body.
Alopecia is a medical condition characterized by partial or complete loss of hair on parts of the body where it normally grows, predominantly affecting the scalp.

Hematologic Diseases refer to a complex group of conditions, including anemia, leukemia, lymphoma, and myeloma, that affect the blood's formation and its major components such as red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.

Situs Inversus is a rare congenital condition in which the major visceral organs are mirrored from their normal positions.

Transitional Cell Carcinoma is a type of cancer that typically develops in the urinary system's lining, such as the bladder, kidneys, ureters or urethra.

Vasculitis is an inflammation of the blood vessels, causing changes in their walls, such as thickening, weakening, narrowing or scarring, which disrupts blood flow and can lead to serious complications like organ damage.

A sudden interruption in the blood supply of the brain, often caused by a blockage or the rupture of a blood vessel, leading to symptoms such as paralysis, difficulty speaking, memory loss, and confusion.

Anemia is a condition characterized by a deficiency in the number or quality of red blood cells, often associated with fatigue, weakness, and paleness due to insufficient oxygen transport around the body.

Polyneuropathies are a group of conditions characterized by damage or disease affecting peripheral nerves in roughly the same areas on both sides of the body, resulting in weakness, numbness, and pain, usually in the hands and feet.
Hamartoma is a benign, tumor-like formation that consists of an overgrowth of mature cells and tissues normally present in the affected part of the body, often appearing in the lungs or liver.

Poliomyelitis is a viral infectious disease that primarily affects young children, causing symptoms ranging from mild flu-like symptoms to paralysis, which can be fatal.

Foot Deformities refer to conditions where the structure of the foot is altered and misshaped, often resulting in discomfort and impaired function.
A genetic disorder caused by missing or defective Factor IX, a clotting protein, leading to excessive bleeding.
These are a type of cancer that starts in the tissues of the pancreas, an organ that aids in digestion and blood sugar regulation.
Hemophilia A is a genetic disorder that impairs the body's ability to make blood clots, leading to excessive bleeding following an injury or surgery.
It is a condition characterized by the wear and tear of the discs located between the vertebrae of the spine, often leading to pain, stiffness, or other degenerative spinal conditions.

A neurological disorder marked by severe, recurring pain usually on one side of the head, often accompanied by tearing, nasal congestion, and restlessness.

Nose Neoplasms are abnormal growths or tumors, either benign or malignant, arising from the cells and tissues in the nasal cavity.
Pancreatic diseases refer to a group of conditions affecting the pancreas, including pancreatitis (inflammation), cystic fibrosis, pancreatic cancer, and diabetes.

IGA Glomerulonephritis is a kidney disorder characterized by the deposition of the antibody immunoglobulin A (IgA) in the part of the kidneys that filter waste and toxins, causing inflammation and impact on kidney function.

Infarction refers to a condition where tissue death occurs due to inadequate blood supply to the affected area often resulting from an obstruction of the blood vessels supplying it.

Heat stress disorders are conditions caused by prolonged exposure to hot environments or intense physical activity, leading to dehydration and overheating of the body which can result in heat stroke, heat exhaustion, heat cramps, or heat rashes.

These are a group of problems affecting vision that may impair the ability to see clearly, causing problems such as blurred vision, double vision, color blindness, and diseases such as cataracts and glaucoma.

Depressive Disorder, Major, often called Major Depression, is a mental health condition marked by an overwhelming feeling of sadness, isolation and despair that affects a person's ability to function normally.

Sideroblastic anemia is a group of blood disorders characterized by an impaired ability of the bone marrow to produce normal red blood cells, in which the iron inside red blood cells is trapped in a ringed form around the nucleus.
This is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by persistent patterns of inattention and/or impulsivity and hyperactivity, which interferes with functioning or development.
A hereditary disease characterized by progressive vision loss due to degeneration of the retina.

Mucolipidoses is a group of inherited metabolic disorders characterized by the abnormal storage of mucopolysaccharides and lipids in the body's cells, leading to symptoms such as physical disabilities, mental impairment, and a shortened lifespan.
These are conditions causing pain, inflammation, stiffness or damage in the joints, with widespread forms including arthritis, osteoarthritis, rheumatoid arthritis, and gout.
These are tumors or cancer primarily found in the mammary glands of animals, particularly prevalent in unspayed female dogs and cats.

A Glomus Tumor is a rare, usually benign, neoplasm arising from the glomus body, a thermoregulatory shunt concentrated in the fingers and toes, and it often causes intense pain.

Atopic Dermatitis is a chronic, itchy skin condition often associated with allergies or asthma and most commonly occurring during childhood.

Alopecia Areata is an autoimmune disorder characterized by unpredictable and often substantial hair loss, typically presenting as round, smooth patches on the scalp.

Addison Disease is an endocrine disorder characterized by insufficient production of steroid hormones by the adrenal glands, leading to fatigue, weight loss, low blood pressure, and skin darkening.

Chorea is a neurological disorder characterized by involuntary, irregular, quick, jerky movements primarily affecting the hands, feet and face.

These are a diverse group of chronic conditions due to mental or physical impairments that arise before adulthood, causing difficulties in areas like language, mobility, learning, and independent living.

Neuroblastoma is a type of cancer that starts in certain very early forms of nerve cells found in an embryo or fetus, usually occurring in infants and young children, primarily affecting the adrenal glands.

Globoid Cell Leukodystrophy, also known as Krabbe Disease, is a rare, inherited degenerative disorder of the nervous system caused by the deficiency of the specific enzyme galactosylceramidase.
Lipomatosis is a medical condition characterized by the growth of multiple benign tumors or lipomas, primarily constituted of fat cells, in the body.
Femur Head Necrosis is a condition characterized by a loss of blood supply that leads to the death of bone tissue at the top part of the femur or thighbone.

These are brain disorders resulting from abnormal formation or development of the cerebral cortex during early pregnancy.
Keratosis is a condition characterized by an overgrowth of the horny layer of the skin, causing it to thicken and possibly develop wart-like growths.
Chronic Hepatitis B is a long-term infection of the liver caused by a virus that can lead to serious conditions like cirrhosis and liver cancer.

Progressive Multifocal Leukoencephalopathy (PML) is a rare and often fatal viral disease characterized by progressive damage or inflammation of the white matter of the brain at multiple locations.

These are conditions that involve inflammation, degradation or damage to the flexible connective tissue found in many parts of the body, often leading to pain and limited movement in the affected areas.
This is a rare genetic disorder that prevents individuals from feeling physical pain from birth.
This is a type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma that appears on the skin, originating from T-cells, a type of white blood cell.

These are diseases involving the gastrointestinal tract, including the esophagus, stomach, small intestine, large intestine and rectum, and the accessory organs of digestion, the liver, gallbladder, and pancreas.
Myocardial Ischemia is a condition characterized by reduced blood flow to the heart muscle due to blocked or narrowed coronary arteries.
Polyps are abnormal tissue growths that most commonly develop in the colon, but can also be found in places like the ear canal, cervix, and nasal passages.
Dermatomyositis is a rare inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash.
Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is a hereditary condition marked by abnormal thickening of the heart muscle, potentially restricting normal heart function and leading to heart failure.

Collagen diseases are a type of disorder that affect the body's connective tissues caused by abnormalities in the production or metabolism of collagen, a protein that provides structural support for many body tissues.

Hypochromic Anemia is a condition characterized by abnormally low levels of hemoglobin in the red blood cells, leading to insufficient oxygen transport to the body's tissues.

Xanthomatosis is a condition characterized by the formation of fatty, yellow nodules (xanthomas) in the skin and other tissues due to the accumulation of fats in macrophage immune cells.
Cerebral Palsy is a group of neurological disorders that appear in infancy or early childhood and primarily affect body movement, muscle coordination, and balance.

Dysautonomia, Familial is a genetic disorder characterized by an abnormal functioning of the autonomic nervous system, leading to issues with heart rate, blood pressure, breathing, and temperature regulation.

Dyslipidemias refer to abnormal amounts of lipids (like cholesterol and/or triglycerides) in the blood, often associated with increased risk of heart disease.

Disease Term: Autoimmune Diseases of the Nervous System
Description: These are a group of conditions characterized by the body's immune system mistakenly attacking healthy nerve cells, leading to various symptoms like muscle weakness, pain, and motor function issues.
Lymphopenia is a condition characterized by abnormally low levels of lymphocytes, white blood cells that are key to the body's immune response, in the bloodstream.
Sinoatrial block is a type of heart rhythm disorder in which the electrical signals generated by the sinoatrial node, the heart's natural pacemaker, are delayed or blocked.
A lipoma is a benign, slow-growing fatty lump that's most often situated between the skin and the underlying muscle layer.
Optic nerve diseases encompass conditions leading to damage or disease of the optic nerve, potentially causing vision loss or blindness, either due to inflammation, compression or degeneration.
These are irregularities in the shape or position of the foot, such as clubfoot or flat feet, that exist from birth.
Death is not a disease but the ultimate, inevitable biological process which involves cessation of all body functions, typically following progressive malfunctioning due to age or disease.
Cholestasis is a liver condition characterized by the reduction or stoppage of bile flow, which can lead to jaundice and other complications.
It is a condition resulting from insufficient amounts of vitamin B12 in the body, leading to anemia, nerve damage, and impaired cognitive function.

Hyaline Membrane Disease is a life-threatening respiratory condition mostly occurring in premature infants, characterized by underdeveloped lungs, lack of a natural lung material called surfactant, and formation of protein-rich hyaline membranes that inhibit gas exchange.

This is a degenerative condition marked by muscle weakness, muscle wasting often starting from hands and then to the rest of the body, and other neurological symptoms due to dysfunction of motor neurons in the brain and spinal cord.
Habitual Abortion is a condition characterized by repeated pregnancies that end in miscarriage in the first three months.
Beta-Thalassemia is a blood disorder that reduces the production of hemoglobin, leading to anemia, fatigue, and more serious complications.

Portal Hypertension is a condition characterized by increased blood pressure within the portal venous system, often a result of liver cirrhosis, which can lead to serious complications like varices and ascites.
Synovial Sarcoma is a rare form of cancer that usually occurs near the joints in the arms or legs, taking its name from the synovium, a type of tissue that lines the spaces inside the joints.
This condition results from medications or drugs causing damage to the liver, leading to abnormalities like hepatitis, necrosis, or cholestasis.
Spinal Muscular Atrophy is a genetic disorder marked by rapidly progressive muscle weakness and atrophy due to loss of motor neurons in the spinal cord and brainstem.
Osteoporosis is a bone disease characterized by decreased bone mass and density, leading to an increased risk of fractures.
Exophthalmos is a medical condition that causes a person's eyes to seem abnormally large or protruded, often associated with hyperthyroidism.
Colonic Neoplasms are abnormal growths in the colon, which can be benign or malignant, with the possibility of developing into colorectal cancer if left untreated.
Hypoplastic Left Heart Syndrome is a birth defect where the left side of the heart is severely underdeveloped.

These are abnormal growths in the liver, either benign or malignant, that develop when cells in the organ grow out of control.
Osteitis Deformans, also known as Paget's disease, is a chronic bone disorder characterized by abnormal and excessive bone remodeling, which may cause bones to weaken and deform.
A rare genetic disorder manifesting as Wilms Tumor, Aniridia (absence of the colored part of the eye, the iris), Genitourinary anomalies, and mental Retardation.
These are physical abnormalities in the structure of the hand that are present from birth or develop due to conditions such as arthritis, injury or nerve damage.
Stiff-Person Syndrome is a rare, progressive neurological disorder often characterized by stiffness and functional impairment due to painful muscle spasms.
Inborn genetic diseases are disorders resulting from abnormalities in the genetic makeup of an individual, often inherited from the parents, which can affect almost any part of the body's function.
These are a group of disorders characterized by the small intestine's inability to absorb enough nutrients and water from the food consumed, leading to malnutrition and weight loss.

Leiomyomatosis is a rare condition characterized by proliferation of smooth muscle cells, often presenting in the form of tumors, predominantly in the uterus, but also potentially in other organs within the body.

Listeriosis is a serious bacterial infection caused by consuming food contaminated with the bacterium Listeria monocytogenes, resulting in severe symptoms like fever, muscle aches, nausea, and sometimes more serious complications like meningitis or miscarriages in pregnant women.
Deglutition Disorders refer to conditions that cause troubles with swallowing due to problems primarily in the throat or esophagus.
This is a metabolic disorder where the body is unable to break down certain amino acids, causing a buildup that can result in sweet-smelling urine and potentially severe neurological damage.
Hematuria is a condition characterized by the presence of blood, specifically red blood cells, in the urine.
Pupil disorders refer to a range of conditions affecting the size, shape, and reactivity of the pupil, which can result from neurological damage, infection, inflammation, or trauma.
These are conditions characterized by damage to the protective covering (myelin sheath) that surrounds nerve fibers in your brain, optic nerves and spinal cord, leading to neurological problems.
Language Disorders are impairments in the ability to understand or express speech, due to issues such as deficits in vocabulary, sentence structure, and discourse.
Sclerosis is a chronic condition characterized by the abnormal hardening and scarring of body tissues.

Lewy Body Disease is a progressive dementia characterized by the presence of abnormal protein deposits, called Lewy Bodies, in the brain, leading to symptoms such as cognitive decline, visual hallucinations, and difficulties with movement.
Microphthalmos is a developmental disorder where one or both eyes are abnormally small and have anatomic malformations, resulting in reduced vision or blindness.
Hereditary Elliptocytosis is a genetic disorder characterized by abnormally shaped, elliptical red blood cells, often leading to hemolytic anemia.

Atrophy refers to the gradual decline or waste away of a body tissue or organ due to aging, disease, or lack of use.
Leiomyosarcoma is a rare cancer that forms in the smooth muscles often found in the abdomen and uterus, but can also develop in the blood vessels or elsewhere in the body.
Amenorrhea is a condition characterized by the absence of menstrual periods in a woman of reproductive age, either temporarily or permanently.

Liver Failure is a life-threatening condition characterized by a rapid loss of liver function leading to high levels of toxins in the blood, yellowing of the skin and eyes, swelling in the legs and abdomen, confusion, and bleeding.
This is a set of metabolic disorders where the kidneys fail to adequately remove acids from the blood, resulting in an increased acidic concentration.
Hypercalcemia is a condition characterized by an abnormally high level of calcium in the blood, which can lead to a range of symptoms such as kidney stones, bone pain, and neurological abnormalities.
Otosclerosis is a condition that affects the ear, causing abnormal bone growth in the middle ear, leading to progressive hearing loss.
Hyperalgesia is a condition where a person experiences an increased sensitivity to pain.

Nodular goiter refers to an enlargement of the thyroid gland due to the growth of one or more nodules, which can cause symptoms such as a visible neck lump, difficulty swallowing, and changes in vocal quality.

Olfaction disorders are medical conditions characterized by the inability to perceive or accurately discern odors, often caused by head injury, respiratory infection, nasal obstruction or neurological diseases.
Optic Disk Drusen is a condition characterized by abnormal, calcium-like deposits in the optic nerve which can cause vision problems and visual field defects.
Nephritis is an inflammatory condition of the kidneys that can affect kidney function, often caused by infections, autoimmune diseases, or toxins.
This condition is characterized by deficient levels of vitamin C in the body, leading to symptoms such as fatigue, swollen gums, joint pain, and anemia.
These are infections caused by a family of viruses known as Caliciviridae, most commonly resulting in gastroenteritis, characterized by symptoms such as diarrhea, vomiting, and stomach ache.

Progressive Bulbar Palsy is a neurodegenerative disorder characterized by the deterioration of motor neurons causing difficulty in speaking, swallowing and performing other activities involving the throat and mouth.
This is a condition primarily seen in children, marked by involuntary urination during sleep, particularly at night, beyond the age where bladder control is usually expected.
Usher Syndromes are a group of genetic disorders resulting in both hearing loss and visual impairment, specifically retinitis pigmentosa, a degenerative condition of the retinas.
These are a group of birth defects caused by the abnormal migration of neurons in the developing brain and nervous system, resulting in a variety of physical and cognitive deficits.
Ureteral diseases are conditions that affect the ureters, such as kidney stones, tumors, or blood clots, which can obstruct the flow of urine from the kidneys to the bladder.
Chondrocalcinosis is a rheumatologic condition characterized by calcium pyrophosphate deposition in the cartilage of joints, which leads to symptoms such as pain, swelling, and stiffness.
Compression fractures occur when a bone, mostly in the spine, collapses due to pressure.
Cystinuria is a rare inherited disorder characterized by high levels of the amino acid cystine forming stones in the kidneys, bladder, and urinary tract.

Cerebrotendinous Xanthomatosis is a rare inherited disorder characterized by the accumulation of fats called cholesterols and bile acids in the body, leading to cataracts, tendon xanthomas, and progressive neurological symptoms.
